482	5	90	76 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency  Review or plan application updates to ensure that rapid failover can be accomplished.  CA. 3.3 Continuous availability scenario The section describes the following topics:  Continuous availability scenario details  Continuous availability scenario environment  GDPS Continuous Availability capabilities  Resiliency level of continuous availability  Eight nines (99.999999) availability 3.3.1 Continuous availability scenario details This scenario has the following components:  Multiple sites at metro and global distances.  One or more LinuxONE systems per site.  Two or more Storage Systems with synchronous and asynchronous replication, with local or emote replication between sites.  zVM as the hypervisor and CKD disks at all sites with HyperPAV.  KVM as the hypervisor and CKD disks at all sites.  Linux in an LPAR with CKD disks.  A zOS partition, which is required for Global Mirror (GM) implementation.  GDPS xDR. 3.3.2 Continuous availability scenario environment The environment for this implementation includes current IBM Z clients running a zOS Parallel Sysplex environment that uses GDPS capabilities and extends these capabilities to their workloads that are not running on their current IBM Z platform. Placing the distributed workloads on the IBM Z platform is possible, and depending on the GDPS licenses that the clients already own, they might need to add only GDPS xDR - Multiplatform Resiliency for their IBM Z systems GDPS licenses. Figure 3-10 on page 77 shows an environment where IBM Z is running zOS in an IBM Parallel Sysplex environment along with distributed Linux in an LPAR, and native Linux, zVM, and KVM Linux guests running on LinuxONE servers. LinuxONE servers do not support zOS.	[-0.066804424,-0.02999493,-0.054775532,-0.061513003,-0.0014192002,-0.052960802,-0.061617814,0.075567916,-0.031641368,0.0042313114,0.021992974,0.058862567,0.07713636,-0.03229724,0.022046043,-0.03136055,0.091987215,-0.021187682,-0.03356056,0.03457