425	5	33	12 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency For more information about this deployment model, see 3.2, Multi-site scenario on page 68. With multiple systems, multiple storage units, and automation software at multiple data centers, every possible risk can be addressed before it happens. The distance at which physical sites are set also becomes a defining factor because two data centers at a metro proximity might fall subject to the same disasters. Each step of the journey involves time and money to procure, install, configure, and test each of the components that are involved. Testing is a requirement because investing in these components without validating that they work might lead to unwanted surprises in an actual disaster. Deployment model 4: Continuous availability The LinuxONE continuous availability deployment model requires that you implement strategies and technologies that help ensure uninterrupted and reliable operations on IBM LinuxONE systems. GDPS for Continuous Availability GDPS is used to provide CA and DR for IBM Z, including LinuxONE. It orchestrates workload routing and facilitates failover during disruptions, which helps ensure uninterrupted operations. To implement LinuxONE continuous availability, zOS5 partitions running on IBM Z in a GDPS environment are required. The GDPS Extended Disaster Recovery (xDR) function extends the near-CA and DR capabilities that are provided by GDPS Metro to other platforms or OSs that run on LinuxONE servers. GDPS Metro Multiplatform Resiliency for IBM Z GDPS Metro provides a function that is called GDPS Metro Multiplatform Resiliency for IBM Z (xDR). This function is especially valuable for customers who share data and storage subsystems between zOS and Linux zVM guests on IBM Z, for example, an application server running on Linux on IBM Z and a database server running on zOS. With a multi-tiered architecture, you must provide a coordinated and near-continuous availability and disaster recovery (CADR) solution for both 