429	5	37	16 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 2.1 Layers of resiliency based on IBM LinuxONE To build an environment for highest resiliency on IBM LinuxONE machines, consider all the layers that are involved and might impact the resiliency of a running environment as shown in Figure 2-1. Also, consider which layers might be in a reliable environment and help provide the best availability of the application services, regardless of planned or unplanned outages of the components on any layers that are part of the environment. Figure 2-1 illustrates these layers. It shows options on the right that might contribute to building an environment with high resiliency with IBM LinuxONE. Figure 2-1 LinuxONE resiliency layers 2.2 Infrastructure This section describes the infrastructure layer, which includes the IBM LinuxONE built-in hardware resiliency components and its RAS platform enhancements. It also covers the IBM LinuxONE central processor complex (CPC) components and the infrastructure layer's key capabilities, including compute, physical storage, and the physical network. Infrastructure IBM LinuxONE  Reliability, Availability, Serviceability (RAS)  LinuxONE CPC (CPU, Memory, Firmware)  PCIe Fanouts and IO Drawers  Capacity on Demand Virtualization (PRSM, zVM, KVM) Linux, Containers Operating environments  zVM SSI , KVM cluster  Container Platforms  PRSM  LPARs  DPM Applications Management Automation  Data Replication  Copy Services Manager (CSM)  Automation with Linux HA Components  Automation with Ansible  Automation with GDPS VA, xDR, Metro  Global Mirror  Infrastructure Placement  Hypervisors Management  zVM, KVM and PRSM Management  Container Management  Kubernetes  RHOCP  Containerized Workloads  Middleware  ISV Applications  Databases  FICON  FCP  SCSI  iSCSI  RoCE  OSA Physical Storage Physical Network  HyperPAV, Hyperswap  Multipathing  Failover Virtual Storage Virtual Network  HyperSockets  zVMVSWITCH  KVM MacVtap	[-0.049866326,-0.023284862,-0.020508906,-0.027224764,0.06