430	5	38	18 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency From a redundancy and resiliency perspective, the IBM LinuxONE platform design (hardware and software) includes RAS principles that are driven by a set of high-level program objectives that move toward continuous reliable operation (CRO) at the system level. The key objectives of IBM LinuxONE are to help ensure data integrity and computational integrity; reduce or eliminate planned and unplanned outages; and reduce the number of repair actions. The RAS strategy is to manage change by learning from previous generations of IBM Z and LinuxONE and investing in new RAS functions to eliminate or minimize all sources of outages. The RAS strategy employs a building-block approach that is designed to meet stringent requirements for achieving CRO. Here are the RAS building blocks:  Error prevention  Error detection  Recovery  Problem determination  Service structure  Change management  Measurement  Analysis Infrastructure layer Enhancements to IBM LinuxONE RAS designs are implemented in later IBM LinuxONE platforms by introducing new technology, structures, and requirements. Continuous improvements in RAS are associated with new features and functions to help ensure that the IBM LinuxONE platforms deliver exceptional resiliency. IBM LinuxONE RAS is accomplished with concurrent replace, repair, and upgrade functions for PUs, memory, CPC, and IO drawers, and IO features for storage, network, and clustering connectivity. The IBM LinuxONE hardware and firmware are a physical implementation of zArchitecture. Here are the key capabilities that are featured in the infrastructure layer:  Compute (CPU, memory, and firmware)  Storage  Network Compute The IBM LinuxONE hardware platform can have one or more frames that are based on the model. The LinuxONE Rockhopper 4 models are always one frame, and the LinuxONE Emperor 4 models can be configured with 1 - 4 frames. Even the model with only one frame has many redundant components and features because resiliency is a design point of these machines. The frames contain the following components:  CPC drawers, which contain PUs (cores or general-purpose processors), memory, and connectivity to IO drawers  IO drawers with special cores for IO features  Special purpose features, such as the on-chip crypto feature and on-chip AI accelerator  Cooling units for either air or water cooling  Power supplies  Oscillator cards (OSCs) for the system clock The LinuxONE model that you choose depends on the number of PUs, the amount of memory, and how much IO bandwidth	[-0.09936251,0.019944385,-0.046684645,-0.040230926,0.004857291,-0.024992269,-0.0059992,0.095671184,-0.080445714,0.0006166372,-0.017502876,0.04844483,0.051814727,-0.05839191,-0.020571731,0.019578781,0.023633959,0.00828703,-0.055876102,-0.065874375,-0.032738984,-0.034348194,-0.101504914,-0.0042494563,0.021980029,0.02680844,-0.010352474,-0.04573589,-0.006166107,-0.033115666,-0.004554617,0.056479476,0.034590203,0.041250832,-0.015854452,0.087248184,0.052279938,-0.064558096,0.035932437,-0.059306618,-0.089456834,0.03670913,-0.03382186,-0.025183795,0.030190198,-0.017461887,0.04559536,-0.016027365,-0.0036568786,-0.023160476,-0.0104851965,0.013096978,0.06391848,0.082367264,0.0064603733,0.042547192,-0.009315128,0.006788063,-0.03125355,0.013704446,-0.023501735,-0.036872286,-0.0030501632,0.050505828,0.03930882,0.0047145723,0.029656222,-0.0366892,0.03237857,0.0028631382,-0.06805714,0.0064162184,-0.02507397,0.04362724,-0.099233374,0.07018475,0.019673282,-0.031185249,0.0204149,-0.017932199,0.035043333,0.074564606,0.009779439,0.0056101657,0.07543208,0.057343733,0.0033194106,0.043368347,0.011646479,-0.024562431,0.05766689,0.12552005,0.07936652,0.011818893,0.0071447324,-0.004996648,-0.007773531,-0.031980928,-0.014650835,0.034175728,0.030695386,0.07405557,0.05679724,-0.04325694,0.013814103,-0.042062655,0.026557155,0.055758145,-0.084970444,-0.034648627,-0.019201988,0.039717004,-0.02368481,-0.042417243,0.07164495,-0.027268033,-0.1289074,0