440	5	48	28 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 2-4 shows the various options for leveraging the IBM PRSM virtualization capabilities, such as zVM, KVM, and native zOS and native Linux distributions. IBM LinuxONE supports only zVM, KVM, and native Linux LPARs. Figure 2-4 Leveraging PRSM virtualization capabilities Resiliency in workloads needs the usage of one or more LPARs along with various modes of software-level control to help ensure availability. Predetermine the availability levels for each workload to understand the corresponding requirements. To provide application fail-over capabilities for multi-LPAR application workloads, implement HA clustering solutions such as Pacemaker, Red Hat High Availability Add-on for Red Hat Enterprise Linux, or SUSE HA. These solutions facilitate automatic failover and workload recovery if there are hardware or software failures. Regular testing of LPAR application workloads' resiliency through simulation and controlled failure scenarios is vital. Conducting DR drills, fail-over testing, and load testing validate the effectiveness of resilience measures and identifies areas for improvement. Developing a comprehensive DR plan that is tailored to your specific needs is critical. This plan should encompass backup and replication strategies, data replication, fail-over procedures, and data integrity validation, which are all aimed at expediting recovery processes and minimizing downtime. LinuxONE can be configured in either PRSM or DPM mode. 2.3.3 Dynamic Partition Manager DPM is a configuration manager that is designed for setting up and managing Linux servers that run on a LinuxONE system. On a DPM-enabled system, the runtime environment for your LinuxONE is called a partition, which is also the runtime environment for a hypervisor and its guest OS images. On a LinuxONE system, a partition is a virtual representation of all physical hardware resources of that system, which include processors, memory, and inputoutput (IO) adapters. On LinuxONE systems, as on other platforms, an adapter is a physical device that connects the system to other computers or devices. In contrast to other platforms, adapters on a LinuxONE system can be shared between partitions, which reduces the number of adapters that might be required to handle a specific workload. PRSM zIIP CP CP CP CP CP zIIP zIIP zIIP IFL IFL IFL IFL IFL IFL LPAR LPAR LPAR zVM KVM (distro specific) zOS LPAR zOS Linux ubuntu Linux R	[-0.0571839,-0.011491229,-0.060906913,-0.007666393,-0.0056723384,-0.02448679,-0.0747615,0.1210731,-0.09799646,-0.02496707,-0.024405504,0.045873843,0.010671678,-0.05704365,0.043706197,0.0044134893,0.030751094,0.011577986,-0.0036153013,0.0078118267,-0.012099524,-0.007454941,-0.072718985,-0.008959379,-0.013371479,-0.00054649584,-0.036424566,-0.00404595,0.004854687,-0.035715554,0.054995507,-0.0012570792,-0.05078778,0.0718293,0.068444625,0.10665429,0.0054180073,-0.0863418,-0.057334095,-0.035501257,0.00014857201,-0.03767056,-0.06636886,0.037440147,-0.016024482,-0.02207195,-0.021422988,0.02790682,-0.013742519,-0.026057458,-0.012690357,-0.08589581,0.13291286,0.08387058,-0.039491575,0.014214859,0.072178334,-0.03897804,-0.03202024,-0.05245546,0.0028354658,0.026759725,-0.048366643,0.017903438,-0.031138614,0.06511328,0.07418044,-0.0059858197,0.028461086,-0.017746164,-0.061281968,0.013026549,-0.035265636,0.029581204,-0.043179713,0.06008816,0.013873785,-0.053744555,0.013150223,-0.013500107,0.039235983,0.070770174,-0.047189705,0.024913982,-0.014119225,0.032555517,0.012582591,0.0016050742,0.06401097,-0.04324112,0.094535984,0.102687605,0.011291454,0.008188675,0.036270242,0.0200833,0.037500307,-0.027440576,0.046625942,0.031598773,0.050307285,-0.055884365,0.087982975,-0.056293763,-0.036492206,-0.011762411,0.050263606,-0.0819703,-0.04745392,-0.013039031,-0.010812569,0.003162009,0.03339666,-0.04430417,0.024856009,0.02710548,-0.058346145,-0.0067578102,-0.04152218,-0.06754672,-0.0003765959,-0.02455038,0.072019346,-0.0827332,0.07743668,0.0190