444	5	52	32 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency A zVM SSI cluster consists of up to eight zVM systems in an Inter-System Facility for Communications (ISFC) collection. ISFC is a function of the zVM Control Program (CP) that provides communication services between transaction programs on interconnected zVM systems. A group of interconnected domains consisting of zVM systems that use ISFC to communicate with each other is known as an ISFC collection. Each zVM system is a member of the SSI cluster. Figure 2-7 shows the basic structure of a cluster with four members. The cluster is self-managed by CP by using ISFC messages that flow across channel-to-channel (CTC) devices between the members. All members can access shared DASD volumes, the same Ethernet local area network (LAN) segments, and the same storage area networks (SANs). Figure 2-7 A four-member zVM SSI cluster example4 SSI enhances the zVM systems management, communications, disk management, device mapping, VM definition management, installation, and service functions to enable multiple zVM systems to share and coordinate resources within an SSI structure. This combination of enhanced functions provides the foundation that enables LAN, which is the ability of a Linux guest to move from one zVM system to another one within the SSI cluster. zVM Live Guest Relocation A zVM SSI cluster provides a virtual server mobility function that is called an LGR. A running virtual server (guest VM) can be relocated from one member to another one. Relocating virtual servers can be useful for load balancing and moving workload off a physical server or member system that requires maintenance. After maintenance is applied to a member, guests can be relocated back to that member so that you can maintain zVM and keep your Linux virtual servers highly available. When a relocation is initiated, the guest continues to run on the source member until the destination environment is prepared. Then, the guest briefly quiesces on the source member and then resumes on the destination member. For more information, see Planning for a Single System Image and Live Guest Relocations. 4 A zVM SSI cluster can have up to eight members.	[0.039233573,-0.03658148,-0.10082285,0.039312925,0.07283084,0.018620554,-0.0116803525,0.06091601,0.008644449,-0.05053317,0.013819757,-0.014794815,0.049289715,-0.028866932,-0.04225364,-0.05510576,0.08572953,-0.04804436,-0.015128902,-0.007901579,0.018490756,0.023950357,0.036725722,-0.032788057,-0.043718956,-0.016729891,-0.028351657,0.025426442,0.019806879,0.009820787,0.008402157,0.098745525,0.008600701,0.0736098,-0.039307415,0.02868334,0.09858764,-0.057330385,-0.025400093,-0.069938056,-0.010072405,0.024197785,-0.074471064,-0.0443139,0.016840307,0.050732337,-0.066178136,-0.009863828,-0.052452423,-0.11825076,-0.026552558,0.024776077,-0.008377157,0.1609458,0.023597522,0.08831998,0.0029448392,-0.03154186,0.010083806,0.025485596,0.037140146,-0.015403057,0.062946916,0.040679,-0.022572223,0.032797348,0.04488103,0.047789067,-0.059084866,-0.05325867,-0.029884413,0.02864159,0.024827935,0.0627599,-0.037158817,0.036405187,0.0040743737,-0.01681649,0.035544265,-0.034641735,-0.027086072,0.084447265,0.033473447,-0.007977695,0.0472911,-0.0045713987,-0.062778786,-0.06061818,-0.023896506,0.044837687,0.03381411,0.08465818,0.011388924,-0.022180071,0.011551481,-0.05156235,0.032351233,-0.05861294,0.051548533,-0.009677499,0.024009159,-0.012185379,0.085627355,-0.081343494,-0.04966836,0.027710214,0.052044995,-0.011160498,-0.02483441,0.050929252,-0.054631565,-0.012215735,-0.06436153,-0.08059038,-0.04095073,0.05056347,-0.021488149,0.025527526,-0.01568813,-0.026267545,-0.024430128,-0.09285856,0.049935028,-0.017683614,0.02248492,0.02507848,-0.06995125,5.4885007e-33,-0.031144986,0.04856117,-0.13721731,-2.8060731e-05,0.050546516,0.03124056,-0.0025575315,0.06049999,-0.039013375,-0.027678298,-0.07595246,0.0075787185,0.046091218,-0.051355656,0.06223748,-0.082969256,-0.018445982,0.0640963,0.0639462,-0.016058374,0.031664137,0.02