447	5	55	36 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency HyperPAV The PAV capability is extended dynamically with IBM Hyper-Parallel Access Volume (HyperPAV). HyperPAV enables multiple IO operations to a DASD through a pool of base and alias subchannels (devices) that are shared within a logical subsystem (LSS). HyperPAV eliminates the need for users to map volumes to aliases and takes care of the aliases and IOs automatically. ECKD with HyperPAV The base and HyperPAV devices (alias) are defined on the storage server and on the IOCDS on LinuxONE, where the DASD devices are defined with unit addresses. A Logical Control Unit (LCU) is a logical set of DASD devices on a DS800 series disk storage unit, and it can have up to 256 possible DASD device addresses (00 - FF). After the base devices are defined, any remaining device numbers in the LCU can be used as an alias by the system to access any of the base addresses in the same LCU. Using ECKD devices with HyperPAV (Figure 2-9) can improve performance and increase availability. Here are some characteristics of ECKD with HyperPAV:  The DASD driver sees the real disk and all aliases.  Load-balancing with HyperPAV is done in the DASD driver.  It uses fewer processor cycles than Linux multipathing. For resiliency, a storage server with ECKD disks typically is mirrored through the storage server function of Metro Mirror (MM) for synchronous replication and metro distances, or with Global Mirror (GM) if the distances are larger. The swapping between the mirrored disks must be triggered and managed by external tools, such as GDPS. For more information about HyperPAV support, see LinuxONE and Linux on IBM Z HyperPAV. Figure 2-9 HyperPAV exploitation example BASE UA 00 ALIAS UA 81 ALIAS UA 82 BASE UA 01 ALIAS UA 83 ALIAS UA 84 B-1000 B-1001 A-1081 A-1083 LCU POOL In the Storage Subsystem LSS (DS8000), alias exist as a global resource and are assigned on an IO by IO basis rather than being bound to a base HyperPAVYES A-1082 A-1084 A-1084 APPL IOs To 