449	5	57	38 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 2-10 shows examples of the most used network capabilities with OSA, RoCE, and HiperSockets network interfaces. There are three Linux instances: Two of them run as zVM guests in one LPAR, and a third Linux instance runs in another LPAR. Within zVM, Linux instances can be connected through a guest LAN or VSWITCH. Within and among LPARs, you can connect Linux instances through HiperSockets. OSA-Express cards that run in either non-QDIO mode or in QDIO mode can connect the LinuxONE to an external network. Figure 2-10 LinuxONE network capabilities For resiliency, it is a best practice to use multiple network interfaces, even for different workloads. It can be beneficial to use multiple networks with different characteristics to support the application requirements regarding network bandwidth and resiliency. 2.5.2 KVM MacVTap MacVTap is a Linux kernel device driver that enables bridge-like networking and simplifies the virtualized, bridged networking setup. The MacVTap driver attaches the guests network interface card (NIC) directly to a specified physical interface on the host machine. It makes both the guest and the host appear directly on the network switch that the host is connected to. MacVTap also improves throughput and latencies to external systems. A MacVTap endpoint is a character device that follows the tuntap ioctl interface and can be used directly by kvmqemu and other hypervisors that support the tuntap interface. MacVTap can be configured in any of three different modes, which determine how the MacVTtap device communicates with the lower device in the KVM host. The three possible modes are VEPA, Bridge, and Private mode. For more information, see Configuring a MacVTap interface. VEPA VEPA is the default mode. Data flows from one endpoint through the source device in the KVM host to the external switch. If the switch supports hairpin mode, the data is sent back to the source device in the KVM host and then sent to the destination endpoint. IBM LinuxONE zVM in LPAR Linux 1 Linux 2 OSA NIC iQDIO NIC OSA Express HyperSockets HyperSockets LPAR Linux 3 iQDIO OSA ISM ISM SMC-D TCP Guest LAN or VSWITCH LAN HyperSockets IBM Linux	[-0.0307478,-0.04058484,-0.046524994,-0.007937493,-0.007527801,0.0013259236,-0.03403788,0.123266354,-0.025669223,-0.04150178,-0.021010542,0.027179163,0.012266318,-0.050767712,0.020226005,0.051927745,0.06096188,-0.0020584597,0.045265876,0.063681275,0.06130774,-0.048898414,0.005853987,-0.079391785,0.013260116,0.0100011,0.034287,0.07378153,-0.018596143,-0.0063916934,0.0023083473,0.038351327,-0.07029102,0.016302863,-0.074196,0.023426177,0.021769915,-0.062528625,-0.11294127,-0.022181036,-0.053081963,0.003951781,-0.047092035,0.025225503,0.02890412,-0.016198797,-0.003985865,-0.008591512,0.016477646,-0.06333725,0.050597142,-0.035358176,0.099864915,0.08111348,0.040158957,0.009398189,-0.05573164,-0.014133335,-0.0037854966,0.008498404,0.016570592,0.041348778,0.020228965,0.06477052,-0.0050895913,-0.020125167,0.059296243,0.06670374,-0.052911792,-0.018888693,0.0074790264,-0.05020287,0.0027472482,0.020321285,-0.02423265,0.07270629,0.021151965,-0.031606983,0.0055951606,-0.026360074,0.039157435,0.08476482,-0.055809252,-0.014225161,0.03835027,-0.037680123,-0.03696075,-0.02261807,0.013184187,0.0087976195,0.070891015,0.15631886,0.037865438,-0.020278778,0.06670116,0.014748247,-0.0063142655,-0.045460314,-0.027008368,0.056920905,-0.004866324,-0.031120341,0.018223481,0.015536836,0.02318786,0.012076077,0.045814045,-0.0336943,-0.09729173,0.034630165,-0.028957421,-0.0058936547,-0.025344053,-0.0062801493,0.026950223,0.08107789,-0.03301019,0.03805861,0.05760947,-0.06230711,-0.09852116,-0.040957015,0.031010022,-0.04282462,0.050110046,0.02787049,-0.041017894,7.8812194e-33,-0.067086905,-0.03913149,-0.11945028,-0.056177083,0.104922734,-0.046658803,0.024575539,-0.029149154,-0.07003039,-0.038297582,-0.054757122,-0.022832671,0.016558696,-0.022181373,0.037584133,0.012340027,-0.021846443,0.013064