451	5	59	40 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 2.5.5 Multipathing Multipath IO provides failover and might improve performance. You can configure multiple physical IO paths between server nodes and storage arrays as a single multipath device. Multipathing aggregates the physical IO paths, which create a new device that consists of the aggregated paths. Multipathing provides IO failover and path load sharing for multipathed block devices. In Linux, multipathing is implemented with multi-path tools that provide a user-space daemon for monitoring and an interface to the device mapper. The device-mapper provides a container for configurations and maps block devices to each other. A single SCSI device (or a single zFCP5 unit) constitutes one physical path to storage. The multipath user-space configuration tool scans sysfs for SCSI devices and then groups the paths into multipath devices. This mechanism that automatically puts each detected SCSI device underneath the correct multipath device is called coalescing. Use a multipath setup to access SCSI storage in an Fibre Channel Storage Area Network (FC SAN). The multipath device automatically switches to an alternative path if there is an interruption on the storage system controllers or due to maintenance on one path. The multipath daemon has default configuration entries for most Storage Systems, so you need to do only basic configuration for these systems. Figure 2-11 shows an example of a multipath implementation with Linux. Figure 2-11 Example of a multipath implementation with Linux For more information about how to access, configure, and use FCP Multipathing with the Linux kernel, see IBM Documentation. 5 The zFCP device driver is a low-level driver or host bus adapter driver that supplements the Linux SCSI stack. For more information, see https:www.ibm.comdocsenlinux-on-z?topicchannel-what-you-should-knowok. Device mapper zfcp QDIO sysblockdm-0 sysblocksda sysblocksdb SCSI stack IBM LinuxONE Linux HBA 1 HBA 2 Switch HBA x HBA y LU 1 sysblocksda sysblocksdb Storage Sybsystem LPAR	[-0.019239578,-0.07800296,-0.043742318,0.015956512,0.038633756,-0.053861678,-0.012554453,0.09123901,-0.06316218,-0.052198324,0.030456435,0.03542966,0.02321003,-0.0034103098,-0.055616118,0.014540674,-0.0064351247,0.045470163,-0.026453914,0.03415843,0.051741324,-0.046108235,0.010459589,-0.054944977,-0.03026425,-0.065028116,-0.015527995,0.025064524,-0.013811165,0.024378957,0.052677,0.05981112,-0.13762695,0.021956779,0.01666078,0.025584612,0.03850893,-0.04443754,0.0060224216,-0.091230296,0.01628121,0.007975358,-0.05495314,0.012374501,0.016023973,-0.024764376,-0.062369686,-0.026231091,-0.043015096,-0.073076084,-0.023354853,-0.016511813,0.026125979,0.13038225,0.01114403,0.039060466,0.013191085,0.048109353,-0.021181948,0.036090177,0.0066287937,-0.032118667,0.06261456,-0.033758372,0.056122314,0.0708719,0.057161603,0.0073700934,-0.042804822,0.052386925,0.0065491744,-0.004814477,0.021842225,0.061498187,0.024060683,0.033337586,-0.0134706665,0.018308511,-0.002016033,-0.08439223,-0.02763172,0.07815775,-0.021811882,-0.035368547,0.052305765,-0.014813196,-0.10892092,0.032165647,-0.04179488,0.00012175817,0.038009353,0.064828455,-0.026787562,0.005405023,-0.02416544,-0.04016949,-0.070293635,-0.00702136,0.002873808,-0.0267881,0.039354198,0.023429504,-0.006506376,-0.028301133,-0.003106678,-0.021612622,0.057732813,-0.04624784,-0.13755764,0.039531957,-0.031647034,0.0050167334,-0.06069553,0.011748993,-0.009066628,0.03642208,-0.07145539,0.09007952,-0.026037699,0.024595255,-0.08067303,-0.093166515,0.030018818,-0.06966472,0.0388386,0.027529368,-0.036241416,6.514966e-33,-0.02642458,0.04117023,-0.06273035,-0.0041133445,-0.0018582463,-0.016458083,-0.029745348,0.033507716,-0.067781396,0.0070796064,-0.07012834,0.0062872698,-0.06372643,-0.06099156,0.046679456,-0.054227173,0.023029823,0.019585064,0.0853551,-0.0038362846,0.040188797,-0.008710445,0.00976509,-0.13417794,0.14086995,-0.02959795,-0.009314052,-0.056820616,0.027289286,0.02471485,-0.0208