454	5	62	44 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency  Object request broker (ORB) middleware Acts as a broker between a request from one application object or component and the fulfillment of that request by another object or component on the distributed network. ORBs operate within the Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA), which enables one software component to make a request of another one without knowing where the component is hosted or what its UI looks like. Brokering handles this information during the exchange.  Transactional middleware Provides services to support the execution of data transactions across a distributed network. The best-known transactional middleware is transaction processing monitors (TPMs), which help ensure that transactions proceed from one step to the next, such as running the data exchange, or adding, changing, or deleting data where needed, through to completion.  Asynchronous data streaming middleware Replicates a data stream in an intermediate store, which enables data sharing between multiple applications. Apache Kafka is one of the best-known examples of middleware for real-time data streaming.  Device middleware Provides a focused set of integration and connectivity capabilities for developing apps for a specific mobile OS.  Portal middleware Provides tools and resources for integrating content and capabilities from various related applications on a single screen to create a single, composite application.  Robotics middleware Simplifies the process of integrating robotic hardware, firmware, and software from multiple manufacturers and locations. 2.6.5 Independent software vendor applications ISVs develop applications that run and expand on an existing solution. IBM works closely with ISVs to help ensure applications that are developed for LinuxONE platforms provide more value to clients. To explore the list of ISVs for IBM LinuxONE, see the IBM LinuxONE Partner Network (LPN) program. This program helps ISVs easily port, certify, and deploy applications on IBM LinuxONE. ISVs can also gain access to go-to-market resources and a rich set of learning tools for skill development 1. 2.6.6 Databases IBM LinuxONE supports various databases. IBM LinuxONE servers are designed for secure data serving and can run multiple Linux-based workloads that include Oracle Database 19c, Oracle WebLogic Server, open source, blockchain, and other Linux-based commercial software. This article provides an overview of IBM LinuxONE support for open source databases like MongoDB PostgreeSQL and MariaDB.	[-0.026690068,-0.041212827,-0.08934374,-0.09937267,-0.0030520041,-0.06395242,0.020257065,0.028376395,0.040734958,0.009479604,-0.0053585744,0.039280117,0.017501328,-0.04043853,0.00025871937,-0.025551083,0.12911458,-0.05617398,-0.024764828,-0.063054204,-0.027168015,-0.020171257,-0.060475823,0.008977412,-0.030011088,-0.0067755925,-0.0033566316,-0.0036618616,0.009836651,0.019301483,0.032051455,0.018180888,-0.080130056,0.09638383,-0.07452214,0.012779511,0.010255394,-0.03302992,-0.04836488,-0.14431831,0.056825284,-0.00045713232,-0.08576988,0.03298256,-0.012283727,-0.024115168,-0.04301168,0.00492533,-0.036320776,-0.03939448,-0.09406689,-0.089035496,-0.015285693,0.14459996,-0.04388159,0.047995638,0.0030572198,0.027651003,0.026619101,0.022618808,-0.0050262054,-0.033391163,0.038762648,0.05108732,0.0049686586,-0.0069327718,0.07928805,0.03752596,0.060804665,-0.088913314,-0.008550924,-0.040895376,-0.06999049,0.00087115855,-0.03663853,-0.045047753,-0.010733857,-0.01991481,-0.024061745,-0.03195673,0.029725285,0.08317809,0.016024051,-0.016996488,0.008991872,-0.018675363,-0.017651174,0.0945478,-0.00080282695,-0.008533799,0.012353465,0.0530435,0.023052298,-0.06853814,-0.031584103,0.021598462,-0.011371918,-0.029155666,-0.0034605472,0.032469425,0.040313732,0.049031004,0.004802088,0.007115377,0.023544684,-0.034340933,0.052810743,-0.0060639316,-0.060190096,0.045854267,-0.0949586,0.015290558,-0.01815128,-0.080958426,-0.0024886653,0.0784329,-0.04