458	5	66	48 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 2.8.1 Synchronous data replication Peer-to-Peer Remote Copy (PPRC) is a hardware solution that provides rapid and accurate DR and a solution to workload movement and device migration. Updates that are made on the primary DASD volumes are synchronously shadowed to the secondary DASD volumes. The local storage subsystem and the remote storage subsystem are connected through a communications link that is called a PPRC path. FCP is the protocol that is used to copy data by using PPRC. PPRC is configured in the storage subsystems by using local administration capabilities. For an IBM DS8000, you can use the following tools to configure PPRC:  Hardware Management Console (HMC)  HMC Command-Line Interface (CLI)  CSM (For more information, see 2.8.2, Copy Services Manager on page 48.) 2.8.2 Copy Services Manager CSM controls copy services in storage environments. Copy services are features that are used by Storage Systems such as IBM DS8000 to configure, manage, and monitor data-copy functions. Copy services include the point-in-time function, IBM FlashCopy, MM, GM, and Metro Global Mirror (MGM). CSM can automate the administration and configuration of these services, and monitor and manage copy sessions. You can use CSM to complete the following data replication tasks and help reduce the downtime of critical applications:  Plan for replication when you are provisioning storage.  Keep data on multiple related volumes consistent across Storage Systems for a planned or unplanned outage.  Monitor and track replication operations.  Automate the mapping of source volumes to target volumes. Starting with DS8000 8.1, CSM also comes preinstalled on the HMC. Therefore, you can enable the CSM software that is already on the hardware system, which results in less setup time and eliminates the need to maintain a separate server for Copy Services functions. CSM can also run on Linux on IBM Z, and it uses FICON to connect and manage IBM Storage Systems count-key data (CKD) volumes. 2.8.3 Automation with Linux HA components Using open-source components, you can automate the resiliency of an environment to recover or switch workloads and help ensure continuous operation. The major open-source components are Pacemaker and Corosync, which are part of Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) HA	[-0.09416357,-0.052993283,-0.054903544,-0.023252968,-0.007408975,-0.031503912,-0.039179932,0.110095,-0.0017173655,-0.00043347082,0.039178386,0.10469229,0.032184497,-0.024963701,-0.011519512,-0.009979143,0.076167,-0.013679177,-0.046261027,0.008800141,0.004033442,-0.07450832,-0.041161984,-0.054089405,0.004702133,-0.023295537,0.053035405,-0.023639673,0.01729887,0.02292225,-0.023491235,-0.014371879,-0.07794974,0.03637784,0.017458297,0.05358154,0.20170337,-0.03060722,-0.067811154,-0.12072234,0.05222377,-0.028430514,-0.1213264,0.012660649,-0.021189285,-0.005452992,-0.03833846,0.05018476,-0.073501594,-0.063716136,-0.059446253,-0.016102245,0.040823035,0.10299656,0.03712735,0.061223097,0.12824315,0.04292656,0.016971901,0.0027206421,-0.04712027,-0.016008368,0.021742322,0.024425346,0.013235747,-0.03199041,0.055504967,0.064530246,-0.021213872,-0.014432357,-0.030694846,0.044006582,-0.021134485,0.02148182,-0.0021225903,0.0015341124,-0.027147334,-0.015832942,0.037321698,-0.048839778,-0.0021459619,0.05508936,0.01376721,0.067147166,-0.010198239,-0.025352754,-0.059605435,0.08143009,-0.035986636,-0.020232392,0.0104403645,0.015496354,0.0015034743,-0.061469,-0.09031143,-0.0049599158,0.025711419,0.01718417,0.060311884,-0.03828108,-0.0066689183,0.04541657,0.033438507,0.018573968,-0.043453865,-0.104437865,-0.018429834,-0.0037627143,-0.068499885,0.03613943,-0.019909414,0.033695206,-0.07285252,0.017436838,-0.004788636,-0.012619679,-0.107014455,0.0640761,-0.104997076,-0.089679115,-0.026381483,-0.03143299,-0.009473191,-0.00088279165,0.059778165,0.0340401,-0.00824027,6.441574e-33,0.0769997,-0.030298242,-0.045355674,-0.037447188,0.013032807,-0.07177985,0.029811757,0