464	5	72	54 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 2-14 shows a typical GDPS Virtual Appliance implementation. Figure 2-14 Typical GDPS Virtual Appliance implementation GDPS Virtual Appliance for LinuxONE GDPS Virtual Appliance provides the following functions for LinuxONE:  Coordinated takeover in unplanned cases, for example, recovery from a node failure  Coordinated takeover in planned cases, for example, maintenance  Coordinated Planned HyperSwap (PHS) and Unplanned HyperSwap (UHS) (with zVM)  Freeze support  LAN with zVM SSI  Management of all disks to control mirroring  Management of all LPARs to start and stop them.  Graceful shutdown and startup of zVM and Linux guests GDPS Virtual Appliance HyperSwap function The GDPS Virtual Appliance delivers a powerful function that is known as HyperSwap. HyperSwap can swap from using the primary devices in a mirrored configuration to using what were the secondary devices. This process is transparent to the production systems and applications that use these devices. Without HyperSwap, a transparent disk swap is not possible. In this case, all systems that use the primary disk must shut down (or might fail, depending on the nature and scope of the failure) and must restart by using the secondary disks. Disk failures are often a single point of failure (SPOF) for the entire production environment. Extended Disaster Recovery: Multiplatform Resiliency with GDPS Virtual Appliance GDPS Virtual Appliance includes the Metro and the xDR capabilities. The xDR function extends the near-CADR capabilities that are provided by Metro to other platforms or OSs that are running on LinuxONE servers. CKD CKD Site 1 xDR	[-0.03909015,0.025197566,-0.020802118,-0.02155819,0.020830948,-0.017761094,-0.01636333,0.056548253,-0.01473468,0.04488808,0.036885407,0.072746664,0.061440647,-0.057817634,0.0057098763,0.020286217,0.031958107,-0.021177547,0.023278162,0.06727031,0.06809994,-0.03931232,-0.045733474,-0.06387129,-0.01922635,-0.024974637,-0.013419689,0.02