471	5	79	64 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency As shown in Figure 3-2, in this proposed scenario, there are two IBM LinuxONE systems running at a single physical site. The LinuxONE CPCs are running zVM with multiple Linux guests to support the workload. LinuxONE CPCs are configured to use zVM SSI and IBM Operations Manager for zVM. Figure 3-2 Flexible site implementation view Running your workload on a single site constitutes a SPOF. Any disturbance in the electrical facilities or in any other infrastructure capabilities at the site causes an unplanned outage. The benefits of this scenario are related to the fact that your data is fully replicated between the Storage Systems by using synchronous data replication (see Synchronous data replication on page 66) and zVM SSI, which enables live migration of Linux guests among the four zVM logical partitions (LPARs). Also, two LinuxONE systems running the workload provides extended resiliency. If there is a hardware or software failure in one of the systems, the remaining active system can run the workload. The impact of a system failure depends on how the workloads are split between both systems, and on the capability of the remaining system to run them. A client can use Capacity on Demand (CoD) or Flexible Capacity for Cyber Resiliency capabilities to activate extra system capacity to run the workload in one system. Figure 3-3 on page 65 shows an example with four zVMs and one Linux on IBM Z LPARs that are defined, and three workload groups. One Kubernetes cluster group is formed by partitions 1, 2, and 3, 4 holds a web server, and partition 5 runs a database workload. The Storage Systems data is replicated with synchronous replication, which eliminates the storage SPOF. In this example, zVM is running on LPARs I, II, III, and IV, and LPAR V is running Linux on IBM Z. The LPAR configuration is mirrored on both LinuxONE systems to share the workload and facilitate the recovery process if there is a system hardware or software failur