466	5	74	58 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Characteristics of a Hot-Warm (Active-Idle) deployment In this deployment, the PROD environment runs the entire production workload, but the DR data center has a started system with some if its basic setup active, such as hypervisors, replication software for data, or special software for automatic failover. The storage servers in PROD and DR are set up for replication and mirroring of all data from PROD. Similar to the first case, storage mirroring can be implemented on the storage server level and can be MM or GM. For container workloads, the mirroring can also be implemented on a logical level if, on the DR site, the storage replication software is actively running, such as IBM Storage Fusion Data Foundation or IBM Storage Scale servers. Characteristics of a Hot-Hot (Active-Active) deployment The most effective resiliency can be reached in an environment where two sites are active concurrently and are set up to take over the entire PROD workload whenever one site is failing or suffering a disaster. For this environment, you must have a storage infrastructure that can share the storage between the two sites if the same applications are running concurrently at both sites. This scenario depends on the type of workload that is used, whether it is a traditional VM-based workload, container-based workloads, or a combination of both. 2.9 Building the related deployment model There are different approaches for creating a deployment model with IBM LinuxONE. The following section presents best practices for leveraging hardware and virtualization capabilities. For more information, see Chapter 3, Deployment scenarios for resiliency on page 61. 2.9.1 Best practices for hardware and virtualization Here are some best practices for hardware and virtualization:  For a resilient environment, consider using multiple LPARs for the workload.  Dedicate memory to the LPAR based on the size of the environment that is planned. When over-committing mem