473	5	81	66 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 3-4 shows how HyperPAV is leveraged by zVM. Multiple IO operations are initiated by the zVM guests and handled by the zVM IO subsystems that are responsible for the selection of the base device address and the available aliases, which enable parallel simultaneous operations to the same volume to take place. The zVM Control Program (CP) IO Subsystem drives real concurrent Start SubChannel (SSCH) IO operations to the alias devices. Both the base and the aliases devices addresses must be in the same subchannel set (SS) to be recognized by zVM. For more information, see Multiple Subchannel Set Support. Figure 3-4 Multiple simultaneous disk operations by using zVM HyperPAV Synchronous data replication Figure 3-2 on page 64 shows two Storage Systems that are configured to use PPRC. PPRC is a hardware solution that provides rapid and accurate disaster recovery (DR) and a solution to workload movement and device migration. Updates that are made on the primary DASD volumes are synchronously shadowed to the secondary DASD volumes. The local storage subsystem and the remote storage subsystem are connected through a communications link that is called a PPRC path. The protocol that is used to copy data by using PPRC is Fibre Channel Protocol (FCP). PPRC is configured in the Storage Systems by using local administration capabilities. In the case of IBM DS8000, one way of performing the configuration is by using its Hardware Management Console (HMC) or its CLI. More flexible site scenario considerations This scenario used one Linux on IBM Z partition and four zVM Hypervisor partitions per LinuxONE system. Using Kernel-based Virtual Machine instead of zVM If you Kernel-based Virtual Machine (KVM) with ECKD disks instead of zVM, you can enable PAV or HyperPAV features in your Storage System. KVM assigns unique IDs to its DASDs and manages the alias devices. For more information about configuring, preparing, and working with DASDs, see Device Drivers, Features, and Commands, SC33-8411. Guest IO Guest IO Guest IO IO Queue (one per volume) zVM CP IO Subsystem Base Alias Alias Alias Alias Alias Alias Alias Concurrent Real SSCHs Volume with Guests minidisks Storage Systems 1	[-0.026872411,-0.048837088,-0.057291824,-0.010405344,-0.019132925,-0.07567133,-0.034291852,0.051776752,0.0023276503,-0.013924713,0.021334559,0.0843506,0.1208587,-0.029564643,-0.025195794,0.038013436,0.033012666,-0.01742914,-0.026986703,0.051063094,0.072882436,-0.02967558,0.0067402422,-0.077684656,-0.013201059,-0.03666974,-0.00039302697,0.030776469,0.041347288,-0.025040986,0.024738792,0.030749744,-0.03792906,0.025179576,0.02836661,0.026059087,0.049392313,-0.04822335,-0.06094185,-0.041316275,0.06342624,-0.023477757,-0.10158543,-0.018399922,-0.025384273,0.070007056,-0.03008958,-0.045852624,-0.09608596,-0.07179752,-0.021854775,-0.05516937,0.045602337,0.16237307,-0.005711208,0.059695464,0.024849204,0.03138603,0.010445252,-0.003336593,0.02244499,0.014324813,0.009645661,-0.0036246765,0.040113598,-0.0027900904,0.1162421,0.022751998,-0.09327167,-0.0016666001,-0.0029463288,0.043511078,0.017282037,-0.0028723918,-0.01473571,-0.0020565332,0.03484955,-0.03358477,0.049804226,-0.06639142,0.013008823,0.07366688,-0.019586066,-0.012939695,-0.003727642,-0.018201182,-0.07684616,0.026119128,-0.051528253,-0.053076837,0.051471006,0.00011312212,0.058571618,-0.025224626,-0.013877346,0.018141307,0.01877505,-0.008802467,0.13052353,-0.041001,0.03512229,-0.010206557,0.028816577,0.013251677,-0.029981056,-0.054265745,0.025647478,0.030434439,-0.13978623,0.0501,-0.03172664,0.031084029,-0.028186085,0.008726929,-0.01068535,0.11003598,-0.019189179,0.08072065,-0.07811444,-0.07754193,-0.06392291,-0.06529442,0.054324485,-0.021792313,0.042447116,0.049408425,0.014265647,9.511413e-33,0.03324671,0.01720021,-0.113436446,-0.049148295,0.067172535,0.0394135,0.03125218,-0.010800204,-0.035050955,-0.018262636,-0.021240404,-0.023199823,0.05079615,-0.028724875,-0.12410396,-0.06394862,0.0