476	5	84	70 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency GDPS Metro provides the following recovery actions:  Restart in place of failing operating system (OS) images.  zVM Live Guest Relocation (LGR) management.  Manage zVM LPARs and zVM guests, which include Linux on IBM Z.  Heartbeat checking of Linux guests.  Disk error detection.  Data consistency with freeze functions across Linux.  Site takeover or failover of a complete production site.  Single point of control to manage disk mirroring configurations.  Coordinated recovery for planned and unplanned events. More support is available for Linux running as a guest under zVM:  Restart in place of failing OS images.  Ordered Linux node or cluster startup and shutdown.  Coordinated Planned HyperSwap (PHS) and Unplanned HyperSwap (UHS) of disk subsystems, which are transparent to the OS images and applications that use the disks.  Transparent disk maintenance and failure recovery with HyperSwap across Linux applications. GDPS Extended Disaster Recovery GDPS Metro provides management extensions for heterogeneous platforms (GDPS xDR) to fully manage either zVM systems and their guests, KVM and its guests, and Linux running on LinuxONE environments, which provide full, end-to-end support, which includes disk management with freeze and PHS and UHS support, systems management and monitoring. This support also applies to zVM and KVM on FBA formatted disk. For more information, see Extended Disaster Recovery for zVM with GDPS Virtual Appliance on page 55. 3.2.3 Multi-site possible configurations Because LinuxONE CPCs and the Storage System servers are at two different physical sites, reliability and availability are improved compared to the previous scenarios. This is also a basic required scenario for DR. There are three configuration possibilities for setting up 2-site scenarios:  Hot-Cold (Active-Passive): See Characteristics of a Hot-Cold (Active-Passive) deployment on page 57.  Hot-Warm (Active-Idle): See Characteristics of a Hot-Warm (Active-Idle) deployment on page 58.  Hot-Hot (Active-Active): See Characteristics of a Hot-Hot (Active-Active) deployment on page 58. Hot-Cold (Active-Passive) configuration In a Hot-Cold configuration, the secondary (DR) site can be a dark or dormant site that is ready to be used if the primary site fails	[-0.03609029,0.015537496,-0.004717387,0.007231381,0.09612504,-0.032853823,-0.017319359,0.058965225,-0.073405296,0.02434337,0.058812633,0.0548281,0.0794735,-0.020782491,-0.014189119,-0.034997106,0.06990831,0.018095328,0.02127565,0.03639262,-0.0024780668,-0.032458488,-0.026706787,-0.040157907,-0.020471081,-0.017679373,-0.019953176,0.048939113,-0.007215161,-0.017979743,0.003091332,0.05040877,-0.07912581,0.036799785,-0.0022657907,0.093308344,-0.00030791352,-0.08065884,-0.11627918,-0.10696032,0.0076090945,-0.027343208,-0.063152306,-0.004959845,-0.00346879,0.07595914,0.003217111,-0.07244286,-0.029722989,-0.012711735,0.034465566,-0.0030687258,0.09968206,0.14393117,0.021616159,0.04747436,0.0055637765,-0.036949076,-0.02715975,-0.02572333,0.009734707,0.009940074,-0.04149825,-0.0053036436,0.046452492,0.03708297,0.075237215,0.017801935,0.0002739758,-0.06175609,-0.0316932,-6.300517e-06,0.005108706,0.037826624,-0.108128145,0.028393894,0.010035191,-0.075767905,-0.009499564,-0.021664703,0.02869546,0.052350014,0.00338777,0.014316839,0.008171903,0.056518972,-0.0721741,0.03664132,0.024779517,-0.008106519,0.06227151,0.08688546,0.067616805,-0.008978052,0.03326258,-0.020527326,0.047278453,0.0013985232,0.06606353,0.047498323,0.03851595,0.056355104,0.039193694,-0.006322078,0.019616488,-0.019877115,0.018429076,0.025111843,-0.09212763,0.03955178,-0.011708029,0.008788149,0.035606287,-0.046738252,0.016039543,-0.0036252611,-0.027647037,0.030278683,-0.044679485,-0.05297976,0.059023347,-0.036806338,0.05881895,-0.057459418,0.05625296,0.082965836,-0.007262836,6.797726e-33,-0.01820612,0.009090753,-0.0998662,-0.05776059,0.03154459,0.022597596,0.0067307064,-0.017435841,-0.0057034125,-0.020293703,-0.05