478	5	86	72 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 3-7 shows an implementation of a Hot-Warm (Active-Idle) environment. Figure 3-7 Hot-Warm (Active-Idle) 2-site implementation example The GDPS Virtual Appliance is a software appliance, which means that it is a self-contained, OS, application, middleware, API, and GUI, which is all in one IBM LinuxONE LPAR software image. The GDPS Virtual Appliance can start and stop zVM or KVM hypervisors and all Linux guests that are running on these hypervisors. The GDPS Virtual Appliance also manages disk replication direction between your sites, as shown in Figure 3-9 on page 74. The sites that are shown can be data centers that are separated by up to 124 miles (200 km), or different racks that are separated only by a few feet in the same data center. For DR, the distance between sites is important because it can save your business if there is a city-wide or region-wide disaster. Hot-Hot (Active-Active) configuration In terms of resiliency, the most effective solution is where the two sites are active concurrently and they are configured to take over the entire production environment workload whenever one of the sites fails or a disaster strikes. During normal operation, excess capacity at each site is consumed by lower priority work like development or test activities. Also, each site is configured with sufficient capacity to handle normal operations. In a failover situation, extra resources can be enabled and the entire workload runs on a single site. Figure 3-8 on page 73 shows a more detailed 2-site (Active-Active) implementation. The two storage controllers are synchronously replicated, so the sites may become the production site without compromising the information that is written (and mirrored) to the disks in both controllers if one of the sites goes down. In a normal situation (both sites up), the workload can be shared between the CPCs on both sites. Site 1 IBM LinuxONE System II  (CBU, OOcOD, Flexible Capacity) Logical Partit