480	5	88	74 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Also, based on Figure 3-9, a GDPS Virtual Appliance partition should be placed at the secondary (DR) site. The xDR Proxies partitions are on both sites and each zVM partition. Figure 3-9 GDPS Virtual Appliance basic implementation diagram With two sites, GDPS Virtual Appliance and GDPS Metro MultiPlatform Resiliency for IBM Z (GDPS xDR) can be configured to automate the process of transferring the workloads; swapping Storage Subsystems disk access; activating temporary records; and restarting hypervisors such as zVM and zKVM and their respective guests to keep production running if there is an unexpected site unexpected, disaster, or planned or unplanned outage. 3.2.4 Implementing zVM Single System Image zVM SSI is described in zVM Single System Image on page 31. SSI enhances the zVM systems management, communications, disk management, device mapping, virtual machine (VM) definition management, installation, and service functions to enable multiple zVM systems to share and coordinate resources within a SSI structure. This combination of enhanced functions provides the foundation that enables Live Guest Relocations (LGR), which is the ability for a Linux guest to be moved from one zVM system to another one within the SSI cluster. zVM SSI is applicable to both scenarios that were presented so far. It applies to a single site with one or more CPCs (Scenario 1), and to a dual site (Scenario 2) at metro distance. In a single site or dual site, SSI requires communication between the zVM images. That communication is normally provided by channel-to-channel (CTC) connections. 3.2.5 HyperSwap function HyperSwap, which is available with the GDPS Virtual Appliance, can transparently swap disks between two sites. The power of automation enables you to test and perfect the actions to take, either for planned or unplanned changes, which minimize or eliminates the risk of human error. HyperSwap is one of the offerings in the GDPS family along with GDPS Metro that offers the potential of zero data loss, and that can achieve the shortest RTO, which typically less than 1 hour after a complete site failure. ZVM ZVM zVM Linux Appliance Proxy Local Disk Primary Disk Secondary Disk Local Disk IBM LinuxONE GDPS Virtual Appliance IBM LinuxONE LPAR LPAR LPAR	[-0.04340095,0.023499545,-0.062923834,-0.045246914,0.061469425,-0.03631973,-0.0011153275,0.09258473,-0.060808804,-0.05582073,0.04768918,0.03312654,0.11538603,-0.006108708,0.013387532,-0.031805646,0.05527127,-0.0046392367,-0.002767172,0.04416939,0.07468218,-0.0058661476,-0.015399466,-0.105750084,0.00028799596,-0.031900275,0.00021667099,0.051988773,-0.0014390824,0.0128354365,-0.004287359,0.0354694,-0.06015696,0.05633905,0.006437936,-0.006349507,0.07500817,-0.04500562,-0.046801083,-0.07155071,0.013906138,-0.030378122,-0.07816254,-0.026338426,-0.03116535,0.12406837,0.028769018,-0.07998866,-0.011130997,-0.065807305,-0.023819508,-0.0073436215,0.046570405,0.17187382,-0.04089478,0.037018694,0.024679821,-0.006742484,-0.04939293,0.01984158,0.012029732,0.0187839,0.029655028,0.018293325,0.060846776,-0.00010829593,0.04306163,-0.023600094,-0.07299028,-0.059607983,-0.030472495,0.018945003,-0.022119954,-0.029268062,-0.09475445,-0.019046547,0.0317545,-0.057219096,0.050815918,-0.109371305,0.04773947,0.10019957,-0.016379349,0.061950147,0.007884438,0.021202188,-0.08911184,-0.03256678,0.011268187,0.006440241,0.09926059,0.04207044,0.07217322,0.03566145,0.032584097,-0.024769748,0.06288553,-0.045742,0.070684575,0.02801515,0.008281408,0.025062203,0.10550197,0.0064824927,-0.0049107266,0.017870363,0.035990607,0.04223378,-0.13911709,0.019184805,-0.027968122,-0.005253791,-0.0015677053,-0.04111363,-0.030148875,0.01613284,-0.037075896,0.04074828,-0.019619206,-0.044476986,0.015846688,-0.017994476,0.06432813,-0.026168719,0.04592918,0.03830664,-0.058639016,1.01205185e-32,-0.08434798,0.02573361,-0.11244415,-0.020989219,-0.009037704,0.048856072,-0.017981539,0.05934337,-0.018378146,-0.0016576351,-0