483	5	91	78 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Metro Global Mirror (MGM) is a method of continuous, remote data replication that operates between three sites that are varying distances apart. MGM combines MM synchronous copy and GM asynchronous copy into a single session, where the MM target is the GM source. Using MGM and MGM with HyperSwap, your data exists on a second site that is less than 300 km away, and a third site that is more than 300 km away. MGM uses both MM and GM failover and failback to switch the direction of the data flow. This ability enables you to run your business from the secondary or tertiary sites. Fixed Block disk management GDPS Metro, and GDPS GM and MGM technology are extended to manage a heterogeneous environment of IBM Z and distributed systems LUNs, also known as Fixed-Block (FB) disk. If installations share their disk subsystems between the IBM Z and distributed systems platforms, GDPS Metro, GDPS GM, and GDPS MGM can manage the MM and GM remote copy configurations, and FlashCopy for distributed systems storage. GDPS MM and GDPS GM are also designed to provide the following features:  A single point of control and management for both FB and ECKD disk replication.  A freeze capability to protect the consistency group for synchronous replication.  Data consistency across IBM Z and distributed environments for applications that span multiple tiers.  HyperSwap capability for FB devices with native Linux on IBM Z.  GDPS Metro uses the DS8000 zFBA support. Using FB disk management support enables GDPS to be a single point of control to manage business resiliency across multiple tiers in the infrastructure, which improves cross-platform system management and business processes. Figure 3-11 on page 79 shows a possible configuration of an MGM environment. It is divided into a primary production site (Site1), a secondary production site (Site2), and a remote site (Site3). Between the primary and secondary production sites (Site1 and Site2), MM relationshi