486	5	94	Copyright IBM Corp. 2024. 81 Chapter 4. Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform resiliency This chapter describes Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform resiliency when it is running on IBM z16 and IBM LinuxONE 4 servers. This chapter also described the means of availability calculation, which is an IBM differentiation function for the Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform workload; the required resiliency configuration; potential points of planned and unplanned outage; technical mitigations; and service interruption, disaster recovery (DR), and cyber resiliency. Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform provides continuous operation and service resiliency when running on IBM LinuxONE. By combining the Red Hat Open Container Platform clustering technology with enterprise-level compute (IBM LinuxONE) and storage (IBM DS8000) technology with an appropriate virtual infrastructure (IBM PRSM, IBM zVM and associated automation, or IBM GDPS), a client workload can achieve over 99.999999 (eight nines) of uptime despite planned or unplanned outages. This uptime can be achieved for data and enterprise services within the bounds of this configuration. This chapter contains the following topics:  4.1, Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform resiliency on page 82  4.2, Availability and resiliency for Linux workloads on page 84  4.3, Framework analysis on page 89  4.4, Disaster recovery on page 106  4.5, Resources on page 109 4	[-0.013747986,0.014938682,-0.048721306,-0.0002333747,0.039414383,-0.0022001774,-0.0127764065,0.1087556,-0.01884413,-0.038237225,-0.03215432,0.07481856,0.04023223,-0.041844692,0.054560862,-0.020488277,0.088764235,-0.03314083,-0.11360156,-0.051408585,-0.039440688,-0.007047352,-0.08180844,-0.01267859,0.019648135,-0.011686557,-0.051852137,-0.030014917,-0.027670583,-0.012839135,-0.049020674,0.008125919,-0.0100008985,0.019386748,0.05754641,0.09201308,0.07202731,-0.043973073,-0.07640047,-0.06489229,0.005575862,-0.030844042,-0.054740638,0.025049444,0.029391361,0.007413