487	5	95	82 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 4.1 Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform resiliency This section describes the following topics:  Calculating availability  Differentiators 4.1.1 Calculating availability Availability is calculated based on service metrics, environment testing, and solution modeling. With compute redundancy, the availability ceiling is access to data on storage.  Physical sites exist at 105 availability (99.999 uptime). As a best practice, use at least two sites.  The implementation requires redundancy and automation for compute resources (IBM z16 and IBM LinuxONE, IBM zVM, IBM GDPS, and Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform).  DS8000 storage volumes have 106 availability (99.9999 uptime) on an individual basis.  When DS8000 is managed by GDPS, you can reach at least 108 availability (99.999999 uptime). Assumptions Availability is based on an optimum configuration for the calculation of availability for Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform workloads that are running on LinuxONE hardware:  Assume a configuration where all components (hardware and software) have appropriate backup and redundancy to allow for outage mitigation and help ensure minimal performance impact within client requirements:  Includes available space on the systems (CPU, storage, and memory) if there are planned outages and workload redistribution.  Includes configuring zVM and Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform for high availability (HA) and redundancy (virtual resources are resources).  Assume that the greater data center environment is configured for redundancy and HA:  Includes services such as DNS and load-balancing for applications that are running in Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform.  Includes physical cabling for networking.  Includes power and electricity, fire suppression, and other items.  Assume a competent and non-malicious set of system administrators that test fixes on a development system that is isolated from production workloads.  Assume a correctly configured zOS system that is running GDPS Extended Disaster Recovery (xDR) in the enterprise. For more information, see the following resources:  System z Parallel Sysplex Best Practices, SG24-7817.  IBM GDPS: An Introduction to Concepts and Capabilities, SG24-6374.  Assume that all pertinent security guidelines are followed regarding configuration of the included implementation.	[-0.017702619,-0.008648847,-0.06355161,0.012816017,0.014433626,-0.05282916,-0.043886855,0.11317128,-0.029598515,-0.05945245,-0.022499729,0.059413113,0.031852476,-0.041282643,0.054309614,-0.009316241,0.09957874,-0.015448011,-0.09823509,-0.021066757,0.013050611,-0.043411486,-0.041139986,-0.04893941,0.017584164,-0.008377078,-0.047897283,-0.002550995,0.016649142,-0.012869228,-0.03004664,0.015775967,-0.032334004,0.015399074,0.060026355,0.046998702,0.056670252,-0.0417959,-0.059893392,-0.027049012,0.012313836,0.020979665,-0.02347599,0.026637182,0.0095970435,0.0016967249,-0.022154074,0.012529047,-0.027176984,-0.024673939,0.013647775,0.052036084,0.06126378,0.13833651,-0.021030428,0.0531535,0.0021487826,-0.028865237,-0.059590217,0.0043417104,0.02608898,-0.06607432,-0.019069375,-0.054466404,0.04842337,0.020906862,0.07807019,-0.083836384,-0.015095704,0.030380903,-0.009740599,0.029226914,-0.012647597,0.019327467,-0.07320492,-0.021895092,0.055847645,0.031322166,0.08542534,-0.00016381322,0.08050088,0.043825842,-0.03511121,-0.033908248,-0.028156476,-0.0052013937,-0.048729084,0.04989313,0.020197494,-0.015376109,0.049392413,0.07741034,0.03704352,-0.042271964,0.017021455,0.018888567,-0.04458656,0.020040223,0.06583785,0.015900072,0.03254528,-0.0195273,0.060712654,0.010740519,-0.025213249,-0.01359119,0.0075326227,0.0027271775,-0.06356392,0.0391729,0.017019516,-0.010260128,0.060483623,0.03840358,-0.027103717,-0.0057720747,-0.07460641,-0.032078817,-0.03234891,-0.026335666,0.02373136,0.0053356513,0.13003951,-0.059098154,0.002759148,0.020887993,-0.0710107,9.467703e-33,-0.004765545,-0.01575896,0.0035756843,-0.08111157,0.