489	5	97	84 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 4.2 Availability and resiliency for Linux workloads This section describes optimum configurations for the calculation of availability and resiliency for Linux based workloads on IBM LinuxONE hardware. The workload under consideration is containerized applications (Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform). Database workloads, for example, Oracle, have extra or alternative considerations. The included calculations work within the boundaries of virtual infrastructure and containerization, but do not include individual applications. Although with this implementation Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform container workloads should be distributed, with load-balancing and redundancy for each, the resiliency of an application itself is not evaluated. No claims are made specifically about zCX and zOS hosted workloads in this document. This guidance is not a client mandate; clients may optimize their environments to meet their needs, including modifications to achieve even higher redundancy. 4.2.1 Components of LinuxONE resiliency The components of this approach are shown in Figure 4-1. Figure 4-1 Structural diagram  Two physical sites at a regional distance  At least two Storage units (DS8000-series configured for ECKD  One IBM z16 machine per site for running zOS 2.5 and GDPS 4.5 (K-sys and xDR)  LinuxONE machines with two or more central processor complexes (CPCs) (at least one per site) that are configured in PRSM mode (not Dynamic Partition Manager (DPM))  zVM V7.3 with virtual networking, HyperSwap, and Single System Image (SSI):  Minimum of three zVM partitions (out of eight maximum) in an SSI cluster.  zVM 7.3 GA 092022 increases the SSI cluster to eight members.1 zVM Single System Image (cross-CEC, cross-site) Site A Site B zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) LinuxONE Emperor 4 1 RedHat OCP Operations Manager for VM Operations Manager for VM Operations Manager for VM xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Pr