491	5	99	86 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency 4.2.2 Network The network implementation for this scenario is shown in Figure 4-3. The implementation has multiple (three) virtual devices at the CoreOS level that are connected to a zVM Layer 2 Virtual Switch. Link aggregation is used to bind multiple Open Systems Adapter (OSA) ports across multiple adapters on a CPC. An intra zVM Virtual Switch (VSWITCH) link collates connections across physical hardware in an SSI cluster. Physical switches and cabling are used to bind sites. Sites can be in a 200 km range for Metro Mirror (MM) (GDPS). This implementation enables network traffic separation at virtual, logical, or physical layers that meet security requirements. Figure 4-3 Networking diagram 4.2.3 Network optimization Network optimization is divided in three layers: Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform, zVM, and physical. Here are the considerations that pertain to each layer:  Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform considerations:  etcd timeout tuning: This timeout determines how long a node goes without hearing a heartbeat before the node attempts to become the leader. The latency for heartbeat control must be within acceptable parameters (a heartbeat interval of 100 ms, and an election timeout of 1000 ms).  Heartbeat Interval is the frequency with which the leader notifies followers that it is still the leader. As a best practice, the parameter should be set to the round-trip time between members. By default, etcd uses a 100 ms heartbeat interval.  Election Timeout is how long a follower node goes without hearing a heartbeat before the node attempts to become the leader. By default, etcd uses a 1000 ms election timeout. IBM Z or IBM LinuxONE zVM LPAR 1 RHOCP Control Plane OCP Infra Node RHOCP Compute Node LPAR 3 LPAR 2 OSA VSWITCH zVM RHOCP Control Plane OCP Infra Node RHOCP Compute Node VSWITCH zVM RHOCP Control Plane OCP Infra Node RHOCP Compute Node VSWITCH OSA Switch CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS CoreOS Co