493	5	101	88 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Figure 4-4 shows the architecture of a single partition configuration with Red Hat OpenShift Data Foundation. Figure 4-4 Single partition with Red Hat OpenShift Data Foundation HyperSwap HyperSwap is an IBM HA solution that provides active-active storage access to volumes that are shared across two physical sites. It is a HA feature that provides dual-site and active-active access to a volume. Data is continuously available at both sites, which improves the availability of your business. HyperSwap is based on synchronous Peer-to-Peer Remote Copy (PPRC) technology for use within a single data center. Data is copied from the primary storage device to a auxiliary storage device. GDPS Peer-to-Peer Remote Copy (GDPSPPRC) is an IBM offering that non-disruptively swaps IO activity from the primary volumes to the secondary volumes of PPRC mirrored pairs when a problem occurs on any primary volume. Automation is used to swap all mirrored volumes concurrently. Figure 4-5 shows DS8000 storage that is mirrored between Site A and Site B by using PPRCMetro Mirror (MM). Storage synchronous data replication (mirroring) is the foundational prerequisite for the HyperSwap solution. Figure 4-5 PPRCMetro Mirror, GDPS xDR, and HyperSwap between sites zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) Operations Manager GDPS xDR Proxy OCP Control Node (control plane) CoreOS Logical Partition (PRSM) OCP Compute Node CoreOS OCP Infrastructure Node CoreOS App App App GDPS xDR Proxy Red Hat OpenShift Data Foundation (ODF) - CephDb, CoreOS ODF ECKD Site A Site B PPRC  Metro Mirroring ECKD DS8K (ECKD) DS8K (ECKD) zVM Single System Image (cross-CEC, cross-site) zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) zVM V7.3 (w HyperSwap) RedHat OCP Operations Manager for VM Operations Manager for VM Operations Manager for VM xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Proxy xDR Proxy OCP Control Node (control plane) OCP Control Node (control plane) OCP Control Node (control plane) Logical Partit