505	5	113	108 IBM LinuxONE Resiliency Case 1: Data center outage Table 4-20 describes a case where there is a data center outage. Table 4-20 Case 1: Data center outage Figure 4-19 Data center outage Failing component What happens Mitigation, workaround, or recovery An entire data center had an outage. See Figure 4-18 and Figure 4-19. There is a loss of all compute, network, and storage in that building.  Have redundant electrical, water, power, and infrastructure to keep the data center running.  GDPS restarts the virtual machines (VMs) on the surviving cluster members, or restarts zVM in new partitions.  GDPS sends compute to the surviving storage.  zVM can restart VMs on the surviving cluster members.  Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform redirects the workload to surviving compute nodes when it detects a loss of compute or control VMs. Impact: Reduced white space overhead for future failover, and reduced redundancy opportunities for compute and storage. There is a change in the network latency patterns.  Because it is an unplanned outage, restarting multiple systems might take time.  Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform restarts applications (or fail over to backups) as needed.  zVM Operations Manager must trigger VM IPL (minutes). Time to recovery of the failing component: Depends on the nature of the disaster. It might be days, weeks, or years. The workload can continue, but at a greater risk if other problems occur. LinuxONE Emperor 4 Operations Manager for VM xDR Proxy RedHat OCP xDR Proxy OCP Control Node (control plane) OCP Compute Node CoreOS (not RHEL) zVM V7.3with SSI Logical Partition (PRSM) DS8K (ECKD) DS8K (ECKD)	[0.015756967,-0.020890119,-0.0058768145,0.06439261,0.12959386,-0.016420199,-0.05364637,0.07461773,0.006667818,0.010189182,0.01278551,0.08775112,0.0482036,-0.048871864,0.025828265,0.0120746065,0.042258777,-0.02763563,-0.10595272,0.00652634,-0.03101034,-0.0006014057,-0.07520373,-0.010186579,-0.012591245,0.031202162,-0.056188356,0.0019763715,-0.